<script>
(function() {

  /* ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
     INSIGHTS DATA (preserved from original)
     ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ */
  var INSIGHTS = {
    1:{0:{headline:"🚨 Critical Gap: Severely Under-Slept",body:"Under 5 hours puts you in <strong>performance debt</strong>. During sleep, your body releases growth hormone, consolidates motor memory, and repairs micro-tears in muscle. Chronic sleep deprivation raises cortisol by up to 37%, directly suppressing testosterone and blocking muscle protein synthesis. Gaining even 1 to 2 extra hours can measurably improve sprint speed, reaction time, and pain tolerance within 2 weeks."},2:{headline:"⚠️ Below Threshold: Sleep Is Limiting Your Gains",body:"5 to 6 hours places you just under the recovery threshold. Research from Stanford shows athletes averaging under 7 hours had <strong>30% higher injury risk</strong> and significantly lower reaction times. You're leaving real performance on the table. Magnesium glycinate before bed and a consistent sleep window (even on weekends) can add meaningful quality rest within days."},4:{headline:"✅ Solid Foundation: Sleep Is an Asset",body:"7 to 8 hours is the <strong>athletic sweet spot</strong>. During this window your body completes 4 to 5 full sleep cycles, each delivering a dose of HGH, cortisol clearance, and memory consolidation. You're building on a strong base. The next upgrade is tracking sleep quality (not just duration) via HRV or a sleep tracker to ensure those hours are truly restorative."},3:{headline:"ℹ️ Oversleeping May Signal Recovery Issues",body:"9 or more hours can indicate <strong>inadequate sleep quality</strong> or underlying fatigue. If you're sleeping long and still waking groggy, you may be cycling through light sleep too much. Improving sleep hygiene (dark room, no screens 1 hour before bed, consistent wake time) and adding magnesium can dramatically shift sleep architecture toward deep, restorative stages."}},
    2:{1:{headline:"🚨 Recovery Is Your #1 Bottleneck",body:"Extreme DOMS 24 to 48 hours out signals that your body is not keeping pace with the demand you're placing on it. <strong>Adaptation happens during recovery, not during training.</strong> Without proper protein timing (0.3g/kg within 30 minutes post-workout), creatine supplementation, and sleep, you're grinding muscle down without rebuilding it."},3:{headline:"⚠️ Recovery Is Functional But Has Room to Grow",body:"Moderate soreness means you're training hard enough to create adaptation stimulus, but your recovery infrastructure needs leveling up. <strong>Post-workout nutrition within the 45-minute anabolic window</strong>, proper creatine loading, and anti-inflammatory whole foods (tart cherry, turmeric, colostrum) can meaningfully cut recovery time."},5:{headline:"🏆 Recovery Is a Competitive Advantage",body:"Slight soreness with full function means your recovery systems are <strong>optimally calibrated</strong>. Your nutrition timing, sleep, and supplementation are working in harmony. Keep optimizing: periodized deload weeks, HRV monitoring, and colostrum supplementation can take you to the next tier."},2:{headline:"ℹ️ No Soreness May Mean Insufficient Stimulus",body:"If you're training hard but never sore, it may signal <strong>training adaptation (good)</strong> or insufficient stimulus (worth examining). If your progress has plateaued, adding progressive overload, changing exercise selection, or increasing training density can re-trigger adaptation signals."}},
    3:{0:{headline:"🚨 Severe Dehydration Risk: Act Today",body:"Even <strong>2% dehydration reduces athletic performance by 10 to 20%</strong>, affecting strength, endurance, and cognitive function. At less than 1 liter daily, your blood volume is reduced, forcing your heart to work harder. Start with a 32oz glass of water with a pinch of sea salt immediately upon waking."},2:{headline:"⚠️ Under-Hydrated: Your Performance Is Suffering",body:"You're partially fueled but leaving performance on the table. Optimal hydration for athletes is body weight (lbs) divided by 2 in ounces daily, and <strong>more during training</strong>. Add a structured hydration protocol: morning, pre and during and post-training, and evening."},4:{headline:"✅ Good Hydration Habits",body:"You're in the performance hydration zone. To optimize further: <strong>add electrolytes (sodium, potassium, magnesium) around training sessions</strong> rather than plain water. This prevents dilutional hyponatremia and ensures cellular hydration."},5:{headline:"🏆 Hydration Is Dialed",body:"You understand that <strong>hydration is a performance lever</strong>, not just a survival mechanism. At 2.5 or more liters with electrolytes, you're supporting peak blood plasma volume, creatine uptake, and cognitive performance. Make sure your electrolyte source includes real sodium, not just sugar."}},
    4:{0:{headline:"🚨 Fuel Quality Is Critically Low",body:"Processed foods spike and crash blood sugar, trigger systemic inflammation, and <strong>block the anabolic signaling pathways you need for adaptation</strong>. Trans fats and refined sugars directly suppress testosterone and elevate cortisol. One strategic swap: replace one processed meal per day with a whole-food protein and veggie combination."},2:{headline:"⚠️ Inconsistent Fuel Produces Inconsistent Results",body:"Mixed nutrition creates mixed adaptation. The key insight: <strong>nutrition consistency matters more than perfection</strong>. Aim for the 80/20 rule (80% whole foods, 20% flexibility) and you'll see sustainable performance improvements over the next 30 to 60 days."},4:{headline:"✅ Strong Nutritional Foundation",body:"Mostly whole foods means you're providing your body with the micronutrients, amino acids, and complex carbs that athletic performance demands. <strong>Your recovery and adaptation rate is significantly higher than the average athlete.</strong> The next tier: optimize meal timing around training."},5:{headline:"🏆 Elite Nutritional Discipline",body:"Tracked macros and structured meal prep puts you in the top 5% of athletes by nutritional discipline. <strong>Food is data and your body is the output.</strong> The elite edge comes from nutrient timing precision, targeted supplementation, and periodizing nutrition alongside training phases."}},
    5:{1:{headline:"ℹ️ Early Stage: The Foundation Is Being Built",body:"1 to 2 sessions per week is enough to begin adaptation. <strong>Frequency is the most underrated training variable.</strong> Even adding a third training day doubles the adaptation stimulus. Focus on building the habit before escalating volume."},3:{headline:"✅ Solid Training Frequency",body:"3 to 4 days per week with strategic rest hits the sweet spot for natural athletes. <strong>This is the frequency elite coaches prescribe for sustainable, long-term progress.</strong> Make each session intentional with progressive overload built in."},5:{headline:"🏆 High-Frequency Athlete",body:"5 to 6 structured training days per week requires elite-level nutrition and recovery to match. At this frequency, <strong>you're only as good as your recovery infrastructure</strong>. Make sure sleep, protein, and electrolyte balance are non-negotiable."},2:{headline:"⚠️ Zero Rest Days Is a Risk Factor",body:"Training 7 days a week without recovery days is one of the fastest paths to <strong>overtraining, burnout, and injury</strong>. Add 1 to 2 intentional rest or active recovery days and watch your performance metrics actually improve."}},
    6:{1:{headline:"ℹ️ Low Intensity: Consider Progressing",body:"Light activity is excellent for cardiovascular baseline and stress reduction. However, <strong>to drive significant athletic adaptation, you need progressive overload</strong>. Consider adding 1 to 2 moderate-to-hard sessions per week."},2:{headline:"✅ Moderate Training: Building a Solid Engine",body:"Moderate intensity builds your aerobic base and improves insulin sensitivity. <strong>The next level is strategic intensification.</strong> Adding HIIT intervals or heavy compound lifts 2 times per week creates the hormonal surge that multiplies the effect of your moderate sessions."},4:{headline:"🏆 Hard Training: You're in the Adaptation Zone",body:"Consistent hard training is where the real transformation happens. <strong>The key at this level is periodization</strong>, cycling intensity so you peak at the right time rather than staying maxed out."},5:{headline:"🏆 Elite Intensity: Manage Recovery or Risk Burning Out",body:"Maximal, periodized training is the apex of athletic preparation. At this level, the differentiator is recovery quality: sleep, protein synthesis support, and stress management. <strong>The athletes who stay at elite intensity the longest are the ones whose recovery infrastructure matches their training demand.</strong>"}},
    7:{0:{headline:"ℹ️ No Supplementation: Food-Only Has Gaps",body:"A whole-food diet is the foundation, but even elite-caliber diets leave <strong>measurable micronutrient gaps</strong>. Creatine monohydrate alone has 1,000+ peer-reviewed studies and delivers 5 to 15% strength and power gains in 4 to 8 weeks. Strategic supplementation fills the gaps that diet cannot cover."},2:{headline:"⚠️ Inconsistent Supplementation: Leaving Gains on the Table",body:"Occasional protein shakes help but don't provide the consistent substrate needed. <strong>Creatine only works with daily loading.</strong> Build a simple, consistent daily stack: creatine (5g/day), protein (0.7g/lb bodyweight), electrolytes (around training)."},4:{headline:"✅ Solid Supplement Foundation",body:"Protein plus creatine plus electrolytes is the evidence-based core stack. <strong>These three compounds have the highest ROI in sports nutrition science.</strong> The next tier: add targeted recovery support like magnesium glycinate for sleep and colostrum for immune and gut health."},5:{headline:"🏆 Advanced Protocol: Execute with Precision",body:"A periodized, full-stack protocol is the mark of an elite-mindset athlete. <strong>You understand that supplements are systems, not just products.</strong> Focus on timing precision, ingredient quality, and cycling adaptogens with your training phases."}},
    8:{1:{headline:"🚨 Mental Focus Is a Performance Limiter",body:"Inability to lock in during training is often a <strong>nutritional and sleep issue, not a willpower issue</strong>. Clean pre-workout energy, structured sleep, and magnesium supplementation are the most direct levers."},2:{headline:"⚠️ Inconsistent Focus: Identify the Pattern",body:"Inconsistent focus usually has a consistent trigger. <strong>Start journaling your training focus alongside sleep, pre-workout nutrition, and stress level.</strong> Within 2 to 3 weeks you'll see a pattern."},4:{headline:"✅ Solid Mental Performance",body:"Getting into the zone consistently is a <strong>competitive advantage most athletes don't have</strong>. The next upgrade: develop a pre-training ritual (3 minutes of box breathing plus a specific activation phrase or prayer)."},5:{headline:"🏆 Mental Elite: Protect and Sharpen This Edge",body:"Consistent elite mental clarity means your physiology is fully supporting peak brain function. <strong>This is one of the most underappreciated performance advantages.</strong> Protect it: prioritize sleep, manage cortisol, and consider emerging cognitive support tools."}},
    9:{0:{headline:"🚨 High Cortisol Is Killing Your Performance",body:"Chronic high stress floods your body with cortisol, which is <strong>directly catabolic to muscle tissue</strong>, suppresses testosterone and immune function, and disrupts sleep. The highest-leverage move: anchor your mornings with faith, breathwork, or prayer before picking up your phone."},2:{headline:"⚠️ Elevated Stress Is Limiting Your Ceiling",body:"Regular high stress means your cortisol rhythm is frequently dysregulated. <strong>Stress doesn't stay in your head. It shows up in your training performance and recovery data.</strong> Prioritize adaptogens like ashwagandha, structured sleep, and daily intentional recovery rituals."},4:{headline:"✅ Manageable Stress: Systems Are Working",body:"Having systems to manage stress is itself an athletic discipline. <strong>Mental recovery is as important as physical recovery.</strong> Build your stress management protocol the same way you build your training program."},5:{headline:"🏆 Grounded Competitor: Rare and Powerful",body:"Low, managed stress in a high-performance life is rare and enormously powerful. <strong>Your cortisol rhythm is working for you, not against you.</strong> Faith, discipline, and routine are your stress management tools. This is the foundation champions are built on."}},
    10:{1:{headline:"ℹ️ The Journey Is Just Beginning: Lock In Now",body:"The first 30 days are critical for habit formation. <strong>Your neural pathways are literally being rewired right now.</strong> Your sole job in the next 30 days is to show up regardless of mood, energy, or motivation."},2:{headline:"✅ Building Momentum: Don't Break the Chain",body:"1 to 3 months is when real physiological adaptation begins to compound. <strong>The hormonal and structural adaptations are catching up.</strong> Stay the course: the 3 to 6 month window produces the most visible transformation."},4:{headline:"🏆 Established Athlete: Compound Interest Is Building",body:"3 to 12 months of consistent training is when <strong>adaptation compounds exponentially</strong>. This is where Ascend's supplementation stack has the most measurable impact."},5:{headline:"🏆 Seasoned Competitor: Your Body Is Your Proof of Work",body:"1 or more years of consistent training means your <strong>body has undergone genuine structural adaptation</strong>. At this level, 1% improvements compound powerfully. Supplementation precision, HRV tracking, sleep optimization, and periodization are your growth levers."}}
